 a chorus that referenced the business apps Notion and TaskRay. =E2=80=A6Th=
anks to a wealth of musicians and dwindling opportunities for them to make =
a living, the city has become a hot spot for employees of America=E2=80=99s=
 biggest companies to bond while writing lyrics about corporate values and =
new product lines. =E2=80=A6The crowd split into four teams, each assigned =
a Kicksaw corporate value. Banks led her team to a hotel balcony, where the=
y hammered out the words and melody for their song about the value =E2=80=
=9CKeep It Simple.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The process was halting at first, but a ch=
orus started to take shape. They needed a lyric to insert between the first=
 and last lines, and employees threw out suggestions. =E2=80=9CPartner for =
success,=E2=80=9D said one. =E2=80=9CHelp us help you,=E2=80=9D was another=
. More phrases followed. ...Eventually the group settled on a chorus: =E2=
=80=9CGonna get you through it, Kick that cloud to Kicksaw, and keep it sim=
ple, stupid.=E2=80=9DIt=E2=80=99s not actually corporate rap, though it doe=
s feature the sentence =E2=80=9CI love the combination of country and beatb=
ox.=E2=80=9D They sing the songs for a panel of judges (=E2=80=9Cmostly Kic=
ksaw investors=E2=80=9D), but then do they just throw them away? So many=C2=
=A0corporate songs are just played to=C2=A0internal audiences, or sometimes=
 to criminal juries, but if you are writing songs that are notionally addre=
ssed to potential clients,=C2=A0shouldn=E2=80=99t you be singing them to th=
e clients? Like you show up to pitch your software consulting services and =
you burst into song? That=C2=A0is the corporate singing I=E2=80=99d like to=
 see. I guess Blackstone does it.
