<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">MMTLP</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One of the leading financial conspirac=
y theories of recent years is MMTLP.=C2=A0I am not sure I can explain the t=
heory=C2=A0very clearly, because it is the nature of conspiracy theories to=
 be sprawling and slippery, but the central idea is that short sellers gang=
ed up on a public company, and stock exchanges and regulators took the side=
 of the short sellers at the expense of ordinary shareholders.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today the US Securities and Exchange Commission <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35834494.260285/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyNC03Nw/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBa187ebc5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">brought fraud charges</a> against Meta Materials Inc=
., the public company whose preferred stock,=C2=A0MMTLP, is at the center o=
f a=C2=A0conspiracy theory, and its former chief executive officers, John B=
rda and George Palikaras. (Meta settled the case for a $1 million fine; Brd=
a and Palikaras will fight it.) Here is the story, as alleged in <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35834494.260285/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyNC9jb21wLXByMjAyNC0=
3Ny5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfd2cc679" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the SEC=E2=80=99s compl=
aint against Brda and Palikaras</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There =
was an oil company called Torchlight Energy Resources. By early 2020, =E2=
=80=9Cit had sold all of its revenue-generating oil and gas assets,=E2=80=
=9D and was left only with speculative exploratory properties. It needed to=
 drill those properties to keep its leases, but the drilling would not be p=
rofitable, and it needed money. Its stock fell below $1, and it was in dang=
er of being delisted from Nasdaq.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like the =
CEOs of=C2=A0many unprofitable public companies, Torchlight=E2=80=99s CEO, =
John Brda, had conceived a dislike for short sellers, who borrowed the stoc=
k and sold it to bet against the company. And technology existed to take re=
venge on short sellers.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When you sell stock=
 short, you have to borrow it from a stock lender, and your deal with that =
lender is that you eventually have to return (1) the stock and (2) any divi=
dends on the stock. If a company pays a $1 cash dividend, you pay $1 to you=
r stock lender. If the company dividends out a share of preferred stock, yo=
u have to go buy that preferred stock and return it to your lender.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2019, Overstock.com, whose CEO Patrick Byrne ha=
d spent years fighting short sellers, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/35834494.260285/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMTktMDktMTkvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtb3ZlcnN0b2NrLWhhcy1oYW=
QtYS13aWxkLXdlZWs_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpb=
CZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNjI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25l=
eXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB439f31dc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">made a plan</a> to dist=
ribute a weird blockchain preferred stock to its shareholders that=C2=A0<em=
>would not be tradable</em>. This was meant to trap short sellers: They=C2=
=A0<em>couldn=E2=80=99t </em>go buy the preferred stock=C2=A0to return to t=
heir lenders, because it didn=E2=80=99t trade. They would have to close out=
 their shorts =E2=80=94=C2=A0by buying back the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0before=
 the dividend was paid out, because afterwards they=E2=80=99d=C2=A0be stuck=
 and would get in trouble. There would be a short squeeze: Before the divid=
end, the shorts would rush to buy back the stock, and they=E2=80=99d have t=
o do it at very high prices.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or this is the=
 theory; it did not work for Overstock, mostly because the SEC considers it=
 manipulation and told them not to do the dividend. Byrne was not pleased.<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know if Brda was inspi=
red by Byrne=E2=80=99s example or what, but he allegedly developed an impro=
ved version of the=C2=A0idea. It goes like this (quotes from the SEC compla=
int):</p><ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16=
px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Torchlight would do a reverse m=
erger with some other company that =E2=80=9Cdesired Torchlight=E2=80=99s Na=
sdaq listing but <em>not</em> its oil and gas leases.=E2=80=9D He found a g=
ood partner in Metamaterial=C2=A0Inc., a Canadian company that =E2=80=9Cfoc=
used on research and development of early-stage, applied materials technolo=
gy.=E2=80=9D (After the merger, the combined company changed its name to Me=
ta Materials Inc., and I will refer to it that way.)</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">Because Meta didn=E2=80=99t want the oil and gas assets,=
 it would spin them back out to the pre-merger Torchlight shareholders. Met=
a would end up with a US public listing, and Torchlight=E2=80=99s sharehold=
ers would get (1) a stake in Meta=C2=A0<em>plus=C2=A0</em>(2) their oil and=
 gas assets back, in the form of the spun-off company.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Except instead of just spinni=
ng out the Torchlight assets as a new=C2=A0<em>company</em>, Brda found a m=
ore complicated structure. At the closing of the merger, Torchlight shareho=
lders would get, not <em>actual shares of legacy Torchlight</em>, but rathe=
r a new preferred stock=C2=A0representing a claim on the value of those ass=
ets. (This stock came to be called MMTLP, its ticker symbol.) Meta would pu=
t the Torchlight assets in a box and=C2=A0try to sell them after the merger=
. When it eventually sold them for cash, it would pay the cash out to the h=
olders of MMTLP.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crucially, the pl=
an was that Torchlight and Meta =E2=80=9Cwould not register [MMTLP] or make=
 [it] available for immediate trading on any exchange.=E2=80=9D It would be=
 a dividend of a non-tradable preferred, which means, in theory, that Torch=
light=E2=80=99s short sellers would not be able to buy it to deliver to the=
ir stock lenders.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The plan was, sa=
ys the SEC, to =E2=80=9Cmarket and promote the Preferred Dividend to spread=
 the narrative to select investors that short sellers would not be able to =
obtain the Preferred Dividend, thus pressuring short sellers to close their=
 positions, leading investors to believe a short squeeze would occur, and a=
rtificially inflating the price of Torchlight common stock on a temporary b=
asis.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">And=C2=A0<em>then</=
em>, the plan was to take advantage of that inflated price by=C2=A0<em>sell=
ing stock</em>: Torchlight would =E2=80=9Ccapitalize on Torchlight=E2=80=99=
s inflated common stock price by, among other things, raising capital throu=
gh an ATM Offering,=E2=80=9D that is, an at-the-market offering of shares d=
irectly to investors on the stock exchange, just before the closing of the =
merger. And then it=C2=A0would =E2=80=9Cuse capital raised through the ATM =
Offering to drill wells required to maintain Torchlight=E2=80=99s oil and g=
as leases.=E2=80=9D</li></ul><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the plan was t=
o punish short sellers with a short squeeze,=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>to use =
the short squeeze to raise money at an inflated price.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Brda and Palikaras set out to market that plan. Sort of. The SE=
