nd TaskRay. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thanks to a wealth of=
 musicians and dwindling opportunities for them to make a living, the city =
has become a hot spot for employees of America=E2=80=99s biggest companies =
to bond while writing lyrics about corporate values and new product lines. =
=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The crowd split into four teams, =
each assigned a Kicksaw corporate value. Banks led her team to a hotel balc=
ony, where they hammered out the words and melody for their song about the =
value =E2=80=9CKeep It Simple.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The process was halting at first, but a chorus started to take shape. Th=
ey needed a lyric to insert between the first and last lines, and employees=
 threw out suggestions. =E2=80=9CPartner for success,=E2=80=9D said one. =
=E2=80=9CHelp us help you,=E2=80=9D was another. More phrases followed. ...=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eventually the group settled on a chorus: =
=E2=80=9CGonna get you through it, Kick that cloud to Kicksaw, and keep it =
simple, stupid.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=
=80=99s not actually corporate rap, though it does feature the sentence =E2=
=80=9CI love the combination of country and beatbox.=E2=80=9D They sing the=
 songs for a panel of judges (=E2=80=9Cmostly Kicksaw investors=E2=80=9D), =
but then do they just throw them away? So many=C2=A0corporate songs are jus=
t played to=C2=A0internal audiences, or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/35834494.260285/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y=
2g_dj1tdHdGWndqQ1NURQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9c93f73f" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
